b'' b'...' b'how do you go about orienting all normals in the same direction, given a' b'set of points, edges and faces?' b'' b'look for edge inconsistencies. consider two vertices, p and q, which' b'are connected by at least one edge.' b'' b'if (p,q) is an edge, then (q,p) should *not* appear.' b'' b'if *both* (p,q) and (q,p) appear as edges, then the surface "flips" when' b'you travel across that edge. this is bad.' b'' b'assuming (warning...warning...warning) that you have an otherwise' b'acceptable surface you can pick an edge, any edge, and traverse the' b'surface enforcing consistency with that edge.' b'' b'0) pick an edge (p,q), and mark it as "ok"' b'1) for each face, f, containing this edge (if more than oops)' b'make sure that all edges in f are consistent (i.e., the face' b'should be [(p,q),(q,r),(r,s),(s,t),(t,p)]). flip those which' b'are wrong. mark all of the edges in f as "ok",' b'and add them to a queue (check for duplicates, and especially' b"inconsistencies don't let the queue have both (p,q) and (q,p))." b'2) remove an edge from the queue, and go to b'' b'if a *marked* edge is discovered to be inconsistent, then you lose.' b'' b'if step finds more than one face sharing a particular edge, then you' b'lose.' b'' b'otherwise, when done, all of the edges will be consistent. which means' b'that all of the surface normals will either point in or out. deciding' b'which way is out is left as an exercise...' b'' b'' b'' b'--' b'kenneth sloan computer and information sciences' b'(205) 115a campbell hall, uab station' b'(205) fax birmingham, al 